  "body": "<!--NOTE: -->\r\n<!--- General questions should go to the discord chat instead of the issue tracker.-->\r\n\r\n**Describe the bug**\r\n\r\nCan't overwrite  TCP and UDP port on ENR when used together. There seems to be some problem when I use `--enr.udp`. The ENR record just becomes broken and doesn't  include the IP/TCP/UDP fields. If I just use `--enr.tcp` It will just announce the TCP port as expected. \r\n\r\nRunning a node with the following flags:\r\n\r\n```\r\n--enr.ip=1.2.3.4\r\n--enr.udp=40000\r\n--enr.tcp=40000\r\n```\r\n\r\n<!--A clear and concise description of what the bug is and steps to reproduce it.-->\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\n\r\n<!--A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen.-->\r\n\r\nI would expect the ENR record of that node to have: \r\n\r\n```\r\nip: 1.2.3.4\r\nudp: 40000\r\ntcp: 40000\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Steps to Reproduce**\r\n\r\nRun a node with the following flags and verify that the ENR record is set correctly:\r\n\r\n```\r\n--enr.ip=1.2.3.4\r\n--enr.tcp=40000\r\n```\r\n\r\nNow run the same, but add the `--enr.udp=40000` flag, and verify that the ENR record is broken.\r\n\r\nI've used the beacon api to get the ENR info: `/eth/v1/node/identity`\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--Steps to reproduce the behavior:\r\n1. Go to '...'\r\n2. Click on '....'\r\n3. Scroll down to '....'\r\n4. See error\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Version**: \r\nLodestar version=v0.32.0/master/+2/0f5ee0e5 (git), network=mainnet\r\n",
